  <marc:subfield code="a">Collation: Paper, 96; 1 leaf, 1&#xB9;&#x2070; 2&#xB9;&#x2074; 3&#xB9;&#x2070; 4&#xB9;&#x2075; (+1) 5-7&#xB9;&#x2074;, 4 leaves; modern foliation in pencil, lower left recto, 1-96.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Layout: 19-22 long lines; for poetic works (such as f. 11r-12v), the stanzas are in the center and the refrain is at the corners in large script. Quarto format.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Script:  Written in a Sefardic cursive script; headings written in a large bold Sefardic cursive.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Origin:  Probably written in Provence during the first half of the 18th century.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Disbound; heavy wear and staining. Many leaves detached from sewing. Heavily water damaged and faded.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="505">
  <marc:subfield code="6">880-04</marc:subfield>
  <marc:subfield code="a">1. f. 1r-25r: [Selih&#x323;ot] leil Rosh ha-Shanah] -- 2. f. 26r-63r: Seder ashmurot yom Rosh ha-Shanah -- 3. f. 64r-89r: Seder ashmurot she-lifne ha-&#x2BB;as&#x301;or.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="506">
  <marc:subfield code="a">Access to this item is subject to staff review.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
    <marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
  <marc:subfield code="a">This is a manuscript containing Selih&#x323;ot for the Rosh ha-Shanah service and some meant for the morning preceding Yom Kippur, all in a Provenc&#x327;al custom. This minhag follows the Sefardic custom of reciting Selih&#x323;ot as on one of the other Days of Repentance (see R. Isaac ben Sheshet Perfet, Teshuvot ha-Rivash, number 512) and it may follow the ruling of R. Hai Gaon (see "Teshuvot ge&#x2BC;one mizrah&#x323; u-ma&#x2BB;arav", ed. Mu&#x308;ller (Berlin: P. Deutsch, 1888), no. 122); this is distinct from the practice of Ashkenazim, who do not recite Selih&#x323;ot on Rosh ha-Shanah (see R. Jacob b. Asher, T&#x323;ur h&#x323;elek&#x323; Orah&#x323; H&#x323;ayim, siman 602). The manuscript was intended to accompany a Mah&#x323;zor or another prayer book, as generally the standard prayers are either skipped or written in fine script while the focus is the piyutim for the Selih&#x323;ot. The headings of the piyutim include Selih&#x323;ah, Pizmon, Al-khrug (a Sefardic nomenclature; perhaps this is related to the Arabic al-khuru&#x304;j), Mih&#x323;yeh, Siluk&#x323;, and Rehut&#x323;ah. The manuscript had blank pages at the end, in which the Musaf prayer was written later by another hand (f. 91v). Since the begining of the manuscript is missing, the specific rite is unknown.</marc:subfield>
</marc:datafield>
